# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: austus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The **12th man** or **12th player** is a collective term for fans of sports teams in many eleven-a-side games, in particular association football.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] As most football leagues allow a maximum of eleven players per team on the playing field at a time, referring to a team's fans as the 12th man implies that they have a potentially helpful and significant role in the game.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The presence of fans can have a notable impact on teams' performance, an element in the home advantage.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Namely, the home team fans would vocally support and urge on their team to win the game.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Thus, these fans will often create loud sounds or chant in the hope of encouraging their team, or of distracting, demoralizing, or confusing the opposing team while they have possession of the ball, or to persuade a referee to make a favorable decision for the team.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Noises are made by shouting, singing, whistling, stomping, clapping, and various other techniques.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In Canadian football, 12 players from each team are usually on the field at one time and the term **13th man** is often used to refer to fans.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Similarly, in Australian rules football, 18 players are on the field, and the fans are often referred to as the **19th man**.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] However, in basketball, where five players are on the court, the term *Sixth man* generally refers to an energetic substitute player.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Similarly, in rugby sevens, with seven players from each team on the field, "Eighth man" is not used to refer to fans as the term refers to the eighth forward in rugby union.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The term *Twelfth Man* has a specifically different meaning in cricket, referring instead to the nominated first substitute player who fields when a member of the fielding side is injured during play.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The first recorded use of the term "twelfth man" was a magazine published by the University of Minnesota in September 1900, that referred to "the mysterious influence of the twelfth man on the team, the rooter".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Later, in the November 1912 edition of *The Iowa Alumnus*, an alumni publication of the University of Iowa (then known as State University of Iowa), E.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] McGowan described the 1903 game between Iowa and the University of Illinois.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The 1922 Dixie Classic served as the setting for an event later referred to as "The story of the 12th Man".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] This football game featured the top-ranked Centre College and The Agricultural and Mechanical College of Texas (later known as Texas A&M).
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Bible realized that one more injury would leave him without another backfield player to send into the game.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] King Gill, a sophomore basketball player, down from the stands to stand ready as a substitute.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Gill was ready in uniform on the sidelines if his team needed him.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Individuals have occasionally been labeled by local media as the "Twelfth Man" of their team.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Adamson, Principal of Oak Cliff (Dallas) High School was called the "Twelfth Man" of the school's American football team by a local reporter due to the rousing pre-game speeches he would give to the players.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Likewise, sometimes, fans of both teams in an annual contest have been described as the 12th man.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Bears currently use the phrase "4th Phase" (with the first three phases being offense, defense, and special teams), and the Seahawks currently use the phrase "The 12s".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Many high schools in the United States incorporate 12th man language into their booster, supporter, or rooter clubs.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Examples of such "12th Man Clubs" include the Dana Hills Dolphins, Washington Panthers, Richwood Knights, Diamond Bar Brahmas, Fairfield Falcons, and Brentwood Bruins.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Campbellsville University Tigers of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics also have a 12th Man Club.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] On December 12, 1992, (12/12/1992) the Buffalo Bills of the National Football League honored their 12th Man as the seventh inductee into the Buffalo Bills Wall of Fame, located inside Highmark Stadium.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Their fans were inducted because of their loyal support during the team's early '90s Super Bowl runs, which coincided with quarterback Jim Kelly and his wearing of #12.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In 2008, the Bills renamed their "12th Man Walk of Fame" as "Tim Russert Plaza", in honor of the recently deceased Buffalo native and lifelong fan.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The team continues to refer to its fans as the "12th Man", with their independent, international fan clubs known as "Bills Backers Chapters".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Bills have a licensing agreement with Texas A&M over the use of the "12th Man" term.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] From 2007 to 2016, fans of the Indianapolis Colts of the NFL were known as the 12th Man.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Colts created a Ring of Honor on September 23, 1996, after playing 13 seasons in Indianapolis, Indiana.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In 2007, the Colts inducted their 12th Man as the sixth entrant into the team's Ring of Honor, then located on the interior facade of the RCA Dome.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Ring of Honor currently encircles Lucas Oil Stadium, the team's home venue.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The organization also designates a "12th Man Fan of the Game".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M announced the filing of a lawsuit against the Colts based on the team's usage of the term.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] On February 17, 2016, the lawsuit was settled with the Colts agreeing to remove the phrase from their Ring of Honor and to immediately cease all other uses of the trademarked phrase.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Seattle Seahawks retired the number 12 jersey on December 15, 1984, in honor of their fans.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In 2003, the Seahawks installed a giant flagpole in the south end zone of what is now Lumen Field, and began a tradition of raising a giant flag with the number 12 on it in honor of the fans, one of whom is Sam Adkins, the former Seahawks quarterback who did wear the number 12.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Usually, a local celebrity or a season ticket holder raises the flag during pregame ceremonies.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In recent years, 12th Man flags have been seen all over Seattle whenever the Seahawks make the playoffs, including atop the Space Needle.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In 2014, Boeing painted a Boeing 747-8 freighter aircraft with a special Seahawks livery, with the number 12 on the tail, and they later flew it over eastern Washington in a flight path spelling the number 12.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] When the Seahawks took the field for Super Bowl XLVIII, they were led by LB Heath Farwell carrying the team's 12th Man flag per team tradition.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In May 2016, mountaineer David Liaño González displayed a 12th Man flag at the summit of Mount Everest.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] As per an agreement struck between the Seahawks and Texas A&M in 2016, the Seahawks have virtually ceased from referring to their fans as the "12th Man", and instead are using the term "12s" or the 12 Fan.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The first known instance of Texas A&M referring to its fanbase as the "12th Man" is contained on page 17 of the November 25, 1921, edition of *The Battalion*, the Texas A&M campus newspaper.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] King Gill left the stands in 1922; the entire student body stood throughout the game to symbolize their "readiness, desire, and enthusiasm" to take the field if needed.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Football coach Jackie Sherrill created the "12th Man Kick-Off Team" in the 1980s, composed of non-athletic scholarship students who tried out for the team.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Coach Sherrill has written a book entitled "No Experience Required" which details this team and the tradition.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] These students were placed on the roster for the sole purpose of kickoffs.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The squad was nicknamed "the suicide squad".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] These students often had little regard for their safety and were determined to make a tackle at any cost.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The 12th Man Kick-Off Team was extremely successful and eventually held opponents to one of the lowest yards-per-return average in the league during kickoffs.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Slocum changed the team to allow only one representative of the 12th Man on the kickoff team who wears uniform number 12.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The player is chosen based on the level of determination and hard work shown in practices.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Under Dennis Franchione, the 12th Man Kick-Off Team, composed of walk-ons, was brought back, though used only rarely when the team was up by quite a few points.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] On June 30, 2014, Texas A&M bought the domain name 12thman.com, which then became its official athletics website.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In 1986, the Washington Redskins (now known as the Washington Commanders) released a video entitled "Thanks to the 12th Man".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The term "12th man" is commonly used in football to refer to the fans and occasionally the manager.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] A notable club famous for the twelfth man reference comes from Aston Villa, referring to the Holte End stand at Villa Park.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Large European teams such as Bayern Munich, Malmö FF, Hammarby IF, Helsingborgs IF, Werder Bremen, Aberdeen, Rangers, Lazio, PSV, Feyenoord, Ferencvárosi TC, FC Red Star, Fenerbahçe S.K., and Sporting CP have officially retired the number 12 to the fans.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Stockport County fans are registered as official members of their squad with the number 12.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Portsmouth F.C. has also retired its number 12 shirt, and lists the club's supporters, "Pompey Fans", as player number 12 on the squad list printed in home match programmes, while Plymouth Argyle have theirs registered to the *Green Army* (the nickname for their fans).
[src:austus/12th-man-football] On Hammarby IF's, Helsingborgs IF, Malmö FF, Feyenoord and Werder Bremen's home games, the stadium speaker announces number 12 as "the fans" during team lineup announcements.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Dynamo Dresden in Germany also keeps number 12 for their fans, as well as the official team anthem being "We are the 12th man".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Aberdeen F.C. supporters commonly display a large banner in the shape of a football shirt with the text "Red Army 12" in place of a player's name and number.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The fans of the Northern Ireland national football team and Derry City are referred to as the 12th man as well.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In the League of Ireland, Shamrock Rovers F.C. retired the number 12 jersey in recognition of the fans who took over the club in 2005.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Cork City F.C., Clube Atlético Mineiro and Clube de Regatas do Flamengo also retired the number 12 for the fans.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The most vociferous fans of Boca Juniors in Argentina are known as the "Jugador Numero 12" (Spanish for "Player Number 12") or simply "La Doce" ("The 12").
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Lecce, an Italian team currently playing in Serie B, retired the number 12 to the fans, which was handed to them by the former captain Cristian Ledesma.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] They symbolically represent a 12th Man in the field.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In the beginning of 2009–2010 season, Happy Valley AA introduced the club's mascot, a panda, on squad list as the fan club captain wearing the number 12 jersey.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] As of the end of the 2011–2012 season, Rangers F.C announced that the number 12 jersey would be retired in honour of the fans support throughout a period of financial difficulty.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In American football, the sideline is sometimes also referred to as the "12th man" or "12th defender": since a player is considered down when he steps out of bounds, the sideline effectively acts as an extra defender.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] This usage is less common than the one referring to the fans.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In most sports the term can also be construed to mean the referee, implying that the match official favours one team and is not impartial.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The effects of the "12th man" vary widely, but can be put in two categories.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The first is simply psychological, the effect of showing the home team that they are appreciated, and showing the away team that they are somewhat unwelcome.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The second directly relates to the deafening effects of a loud crowd.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In Association football, the crowd can be very passionate and often sing throughout the whole match.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Some occasions where the crowd noise is extra loud can be before kickoff; during the buildup to and scoring of a goal; when encouraging the team to come back from defeat; to discourage an opposition penalty taker; or to harass a referee giving a free kick to the opposition team.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In American football, fans are most incited by physical play, especially good plays made by the defense.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Additionally, the home team can derive energy from the loud noise of their fans; former American football players have described the feeling of their adrenaline pumping after hearing the fans yell, which is "like you have a reserve energy tank".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The noise of the crowd can have a significant impact on the players on the field.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In American football, an extremely loud crowd can prevent the offensive linemen from hearing the snap count.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] This can have the effect of making the player slower to react when the ball is snapped, and his eventual response may be weaker than normal because each play is begun "with some indecision and doubt".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The noise can also prevent players from hearing audibles and can make it difficult for the team's offense to coordinate plays in the huddle.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The effect of the noise can often be measured in mistakes, such as false start penalties.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Coaches can take steps to minimize the effect of the crowd noise on their teams.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Some American football teams bring large speakers to their practice fields and broadcast loud noises such as jet engines to prepare their teams for the anticipated noise level.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Crowd noise tends to diminish after a long lull in play, such as a pause for instant replay.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Former NFL player Brian Baldinger speculates that some coaches draw out reviews as part of a coaching strategy to quiet the crowd for their next play.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] A researcher from Harvard University discovered in a study that some association football referees appeared to be impacted by crowd noise.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] His studies revealed that a home team acquired an additional 0.1 goal advantage for every 10,000 fans in the stadium.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Delia Smith, Norwich City's joint major shareholder, received some attention when she took to the pitch during a half time interval, with a microphone in hand and Sky TV cameras in tow, to tell fans the side "need their twelfth man".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Norwich City lost the game in the final seconds, but Smith's passion worked to increase the affection the fans held for her.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The current naturally loudest football stadium is Nef Stadium in Istanbul home of Galatasaray S.K.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] As a prepared attempt, the current world record for crowd noise at an athletic event was set on September 29, 2014, when the Kansas City Chiefs hosted the New England Patriots.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Noise during that event reached a high of 142.2 decibels during a timeout.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Texas A&M University applied on December 26, 1989, for trademark U.S.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The United States Patent and Trademark Office issued the "trademark registration" September 4, 1990, to Texas A&M.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Four additional Trademark claims related to the "12th Man" term were also filed and granted at later dates by Texas A&M University (See U.S.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] 74560726, 76671314, 85977835 and 85851199), the first three of which have achieved Incontestable Status as a result of its section 15 affidavit with the Patent and Trademark Office.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] According to former Texas A&M Athletic Director Bill Byrne, he contacted the Chicago Bears and Buffalo Bills about halting their "12th Man" themes.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Byrne stated that, "they responded quickly with our requests to stop using our Twelfth Man trademark".
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Texas A&M sent requests to stop using the phrase to the Seattle Seahawks in both 2004 and 2005.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The Seahawks did not respond to the requests.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In January 2006, Texas A&M filed a trademark infringement lawsuit against the Seattle Seahawks and in May 2006, the dispute was settled out of court.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] Neither side admitted any fault or liability.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In the agreement, the Seahawks licensed the phrase in exchange for $100,000, along with public acknowledgement as to Texas A&M's ownership rights of the phrase, and an additional annual fee.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The compensation amounted to $5,000 per year.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The agreement, which expired in 2016, limited the Seahawks' usage to seven western states and forbid them from selling any "12th Man" merchandise.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In August 2015, the Seahawks shifted towards calling their fans the "12s", and replaced their "Home of the 12th Man" stadium sign with a new "Home of the 12s" sign.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] On November 12, 2015, Texas A&M filed suit against the Indianapolis Colts after repeated cease and desist requests were ignored by the NFL team.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] In August 2016, the Seahawks agreed to a new five-year trademark licensing agreement with Texas A&M.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] As part of the agreement, the Seahawks agreed to pay Texas A&M $140,000 for limited rights to use the trademarked term.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] This agreement, like the previous agreement, prohibits the Seahawks from using the "12th Man" term on any merchandise.
[src:austus/12th-man-football] The new agreement, however, also prohibits Seattle from using the term on social media, nor are they allowed to use the term on any signage within their stadium, including their Ring of Honor.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:austus/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:austus/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:austus/a7fl] The **American 7s Football League** (**A7FL**) is a sports league in the United States which plays a seven-man version of gridiron football called American 7s Football.
[src:austus/a7fl] Launched in 2015, its games are played without football helmets or other protective equipment.
[src:austus/a7fl] League players are not paid during the season and most of them are primarily amateurs.
[src:austus/a7fl] Instead cash prizes are awarded to division and national champs (divided among the roster of roughly 25 players).
[src:austus/a7fl] For the 2022 season the prize pool was $50,000.
[src:austus/a7fl] Founded in 2014 with play commencing the following year, the A7FL plays a seven-game schedule running from March to May, with playoffs running from June to July.
[src:austus/a7fl] It can trace it history to a New York metropolitan area league called **Town Beef** that started in 2008 and played 7-on-7 full-contact football with no helmets or pads.
[src:austus/a7fl] North Jersey remains one of the two nuclei around which the A7FL's teams are based, the other being the Las Vegas Valley.
[src:austus/a7fl] The league primarily attracts semi-professional football players seeking opportunities to stay in shape during spring.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2016, the league participated in a safety study led by the New Jersey Institute of Technology.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2023, the league had its first former NFL starter sign with a team, that being cornerback Dominique Rodgers-Cromartie, who signed with the Tampa Nightcrawlers.
[src:austus/a7fl] A7FL players play without pads or helmets as part of what the league describes as an effort to reduce the potential of head injuries resulting from helmet-to-helmet contact.
[src:austus/a7fl] League games also do not include kickoffs, field goals, or punts, and, instead of the kickoff, implement a unique version of special teams called a 3-on-1 throw off (three 'throwing' players and one receiver).
[src:austus/a7fl] Games are played on narrow fields of 37 yards' width (34 m, between one set of hash marks and the furthest sideline away) to accommodate fewer players on the field on each team.
[src:austus/a7fl] A7FL games are played between two seven-man teams; teams are, additionally, required to cap their rosters at 35 active players.
[src:austus/a7fl] Teams that will participate in the 2026 season.
[src:austus/a7fl] Eleven Sports Network acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to broadcast the A7FL 2017 Championship on July 9, 2017, played at Palisades Credit Union Park.
[src:austus/a7fl] Through Eleven Sports Network's distribution with DirecTV, Verizon FiOS, and AT&T uVerse the A7FL 2017 Championship was to be accessible by over 70 million homes worldwide.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2018, Eleven Sports Network acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to broadcast a 21-game package including the playoffs and championship, and in 2019, the non-exclusive U.S. and international rights to the playoffs and championship.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2019, Twitch acquired the exclusive United States and international rights to a 21-game package of the season including the playoffs and championship.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2020, A7FL again partnered with Eleven Sports Network for the exclusive United States and international rights of the season, including the playoffs and championship.
[src:austus/a7fl] For 2021, FITE TV acquired the United States and international rights to the A7FL's season including the playoffs and championship.
[src:austus/a7fl] Starting in 2022, select Games of the Week -- including the playoffs and championship - were broadcast on Stadium (sports network), YouTube, DAZN, and A7FL.tv.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2025, select A7FL Games of the Week including the playoffs and championship and A7FL InMotion, a weekly 30 minute show featuring a look inside the A7FL -- are broadcast on Fox Soul, Stadium (sports network), DAZN, Triller TV, YouTube, and A7FL.tv.
[src:austus/a7fl] The CEO of the A7FL is Sener Korkusuz and its president is Ryan DePaul.
[src:austus/a7fl] In 2019, UFC co-founder David Isaacs joined the A7FL to serve as chairman of the advisory board.
[src:austus/a7fl] Isaacs said, "Removing equipment to make any sport safer seems counterintuitive and we faced similar issues when we launched the UFC and created the sport of mixed martial arts.
[src:austus/a7fl] With the A7FL, football can be safer but still thrilling full-contact competition.
[src:austus/a7fl] Athletes playing in the A7FL are required to sign a player injury waiver and be 18 years of age or older.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:austus/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] The league was founded as the **Federal Territory Australian Rules Football League** in 1924 with founding members Acton and Queanbeyan.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] The following year, the premiership was contested by 4 clubs including Canberra, Federal and Duntroon.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] By 1926 the competition had gained popularity and was contested by 5 clubs.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] In November 2010 the five AFL Canberra Premier Division clubs merged with the Premier Division clubs of the Queensland Australian Football League to form the North East Australian Football League.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] From 2011 onwards, the AFL Canberra Premier Division together with the reserve sides from the Sydney Swans and Greater Western Sydney Giants would form the NEAFL Eastern Conference.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] However the NEAFL was later dissolved due primarily to the COVID pandemic and associated financial pressures.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] The AFL Canberra has been through a number of forms.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] Clubs listed by highest grade of competition.
[src:austus/afl-canberra-p01] Point colours indicate club's highest level of competition.
[src:austus/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:austus/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:austus/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:austus/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:austus/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:austus/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:austus/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:austus/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:austus/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:austus/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:austus/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:austus/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:austus/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:austus/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:austus/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:austus/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:austus/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:austus/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:austus/austus] The game is played with a gridiron ball and features both punting and forward passing, with Australian rules football style marking providing the opportunity for a free kick or throw and the absence of an offside rule.
[src:austus/austus] To enable football competitions between Australians and Americans, a modified code was proposed.
[src:austus/austus] Although sometimes described as a hybrid between the Australian and American codes, creator Ern Cowley described it as "99% Australian rules with the addition of gridiron highlights".
[src:austus/austus] The only significant rule change from the Australian game was that the American football-style forward pass was allowed and afforded the same benefits as an Australian rules football kick.
[src:austus/austus] The game was played with an American football rather than an Australian football, because the pointed design of the American ball meant that it could be both thrown and kicked.
[src:austus/austus] These rules enabled Americans to participate against Australians at Australian rules football using the ball skills they already possessed from playing American football.
[src:austus/austus] The first game of Austus was played on 18 July 1943 at Punt Road Oval between a team of US Servicemen and an Australian Explosives Factory team over two 25-minute halves.
[src:austus/austus] Two weeks later, an Australian team including around twelve VFL players comfortably defeated the Americans 17.23 (125) d.
[src:austus/austus] Archival footage of the game exists (Video on YouTube), exhibiting American players preference to run and forward pass the ball.
[src:austus/austus] Several more games were played as exhibitions in 1943 and 1944.
[src:austus/austus] By the end of 1943, both countries' armed forces endorsed the game as a suitable activity for their troops, with the rules later published in official army publications.
[src:austus/austus] The US Army noted that the game was more suited to warmer climates than the American game, and was more convenient as it could be played without protective equipment.
[src:austus/austus] The rules are credited to *The Sporting Globe* sportswriter and former Carlton player Ern Cowley.
[src:austus/austus] Cowley and leading American player Private Bill Jost, who was a prodigious throw and captained the American teams, were both presented medals by the Helms Athletic Foundation in 1944 for their services to the short-lived code.
[src:austus/austus] The game disappeared after the large scale departures of American soldiers from Australia in 1945.
[src:austus/austus] Some consideration was given in 1946 to send Australian teams to America to demonstrate the sport but an absence of willing financial backers meant that the idea quickly fell through.
[src:austus/austus] It is almost certain that 1945 or 1946 were the last year the game was ever played.
[src:austus/austus] "'Austus' and baseball on Allies' Sports Day".
[src:austus/austus] "Americans not keen for Aust. football tour".
[src:austus/austus] "Austus: The wartime football that blended Australian and American gridiron rules".
